{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565967","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565967"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:35:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:35:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18670"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18670","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18670"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.05,0.19,0.51,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11402"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111553"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11402"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18670"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93642"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1578"},{"type":"tags","id":"1787"},{"type":"tags","id":"2524"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26417"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33311"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39123"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39783"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40560"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111553","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111553"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of progressive exertional dyspnoea and orthopnoea. He reports worsening breathlessness especially when lying flat, which interferes with sleep. The patient specifically mentions that his breathing problems began shortly after recovering from his rib injuries. He sustained multiple rib fractures in a motor vehicle accident eight months ago. He has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He works as an accountant in an office environment with no exposure to dust or chemicals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is reduced chest expansion on the right side and decreased breath sounds at the right base. Joint examination is unremarkable. The rest of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPulmonary function tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EForced expiratory volume in one second (FEV1): 2.1 L (65% predicted)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EForced vital capacity (FVC): 2.5 L (62% predicted)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFEV1/FVC ratio: 0.86\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal lung capacity: 4.2 L (65% predicted)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDiffusing capacity for carbon monoxide: 22 mL/min/mmHg (85% predicted)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECarbon monoxide transfer coefficient (KCO): 4.8 mL/min/mmHg/L (95% predicted)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChest X-ray shows an elevated right hemidiaphragm with no evidence of parenchymal lung disease.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation to confirm the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fluoroscopic sniff test","Echocardiogram","Nerve conduction studies","High-resolution computed tomography of chest","Cardiopulmonary exercise test"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of right hemidiaphragm paralysis following thoracic trauma. The characteristic features include dyspnoea, orthopnoea that interferes with sleep, and reduced chest expansion on the affected side with decreased breath sounds at the right base. The temporal relationship between the trauma and symptom onset is a key diagnostic clue. The pulmonary function tests show a restrictive pattern (reduced FEV1 and FVC with preserved ratio) with preserved gas transfer, which is typical of diaphragm paralysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluoroscopic sniff test\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard investigation for diagnosing diaphragm paralysis. During the test, paradoxical upward movement of the affected hemidiaphragm during sniffing indicates paralysis. This dynamic test provides real-time visualisation of diaphragm movement and can definitively confirm the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEchocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E would assess cardiac structure and function but would not be helpful in diagnosing diaphragm paralysis. While cardiac causes of dyspnoea should be considered, the clinical presentation with orthopnoea, unilateral chest findings, and elevated hemidiaphragm on chest X-ray strongly suggests diaphragm pathology rather than cardiac disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENerve conduction studies\u003C/strong\u003E of the phrenic nerve can be performed but are technically challenging and not routinely available. They may help determine if the paralysis is due to nerve injury but would not be the first-line investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh-resolution computed tomography of chest\u003C/strong\u003E would provide detailed anatomical information and may show an elevated hemidiaphragm, but it cannot assess diaphragm function dynamically. It cannot distinguish between an elevated but functioning diaphragm and true paralysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiopulmonary exercise test\u003C/strong\u003E would provide information about exercise capacity and the physiological response to exercise, including ventilatory limitation. While it may show reduced exercise capacity and abnormal breathing patterns in diaphragm paralysis, it cannot specifically diagnose diaphragm dysfunction or distinguish it from other causes of exertional dyspnoea.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Unilateral diaphragm paralysis typically presents with dyspnoea and orthopnoea, with characteristic reduction in lung volumes but preserved gas transfer.","Sniff testing using fluoroscopy is the gold standard investigation for diagnosing diaphragm paralysis.","Prior thoracic trauma is a common cause of unilateral diaphragm paralysis."],"references":["Kokatnur L, Rudrappa M. Diaphragmatic palsy. Diseases. 2018 Feb 13;6(1):16."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93642"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18670"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93642","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93642"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-16T17:46:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-16T17:47:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11402"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111553"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u